abstract = {Tropical rainforests are a major compartment of global biochemical cycles. Today these biomes are threatened by climate change and deforestation. Estimating the response of the productivity of these biomes to climate variability is a great challenge. This study investigate the potential of a forest gap model to assess carbon fluxes of a trop- ical rainforest located in French Guyana at yearly and daily time scale under variable climate. Forest model simulations were linked with eddy covariance measurements of gross primary production (GPP), respiration and net ecosystem production (NEP) in order to analyze individual model processes that describe the limitation of productivity and respiration due to temperature and water stress. Four parameterizations were de- veloped and compared with each other regarding their potential to reproduce observed carbon fluxes. One parameterization based mainly on literature, the other three param- eterizations resulting from different numerical calibration processes. The study shows that, in general, the forest model is capable to simulate the observed carbon fluxes under variable climate. Deviations between observed and simulated data could be ob- served on days with extreme climate conditions. Furthermore, the influence of climate change on the tropical forest in French Guyana is analyzed using two climate change scenarios as predicted by the IPCC. In order to understand the impact of the climate change on the forest in French Guyana, seasonal variations in daily carbon fluxes were analyzed. The simulation has shown that increasing CO2 and temperature leading to an likewise increase in productivity and respiration. NEP remains positive during the climate change scenario. After a recovery time the model outcome shows a biomass increase of early and mid successional trees. This could be a sign for a resilience of the forest in French Guyana under climate change due to a shift in PFT dominate toward early successional trees